'''Ni-Vanuatu names''' are the names used by the people of [[Vanuatu]], who are commonly known as [[ni-Vanuatu]]. Under the [[law of Vanuatu]], a child's name registered at birth should include "the family name, the Christian name, if any, and the Melanesian individual name", the latter of which is also known as a "traditional name" or "custom name".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paclii.org/vu/legis/consol_act1988/csa308/|chapter=Civil Status (Registration) Act [Cap 61]|title=Vanuatu Consolidated Legislation|year=1988|publisher=Pacific Islands Legal Information Institute|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref><ref name="OHCHR">{{cite web|url=http://www.unhchr.ch/tbs/doc.nsf/(Symbol)/a84e86cab5dee25680256739003c1782?Opendocument|title=Country Analysis: Vanuatu|date=1999-02-05|publisher=Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref>
Naming customs differ between the various [[List of islands of Vanuatu|islands which comprise Vanuatu]]. The decision whether to give a child a custom name and/or "foreign name" may be tied to the parents' expectations of the child's future life path: whether he would remain in his village and inherit his ancestors' property and social roles, or whether he would leave to pursue a career elsewhere.<ref>{{cite book|first=Robert J.|last=Gregory|first2=Janet E.|last2=Gregory|chapter=Custom and Western Medicine: The Ethics of Intervention|editor-first=Awadesh N.|editor-last=Sharma|editor2-first=Rajesh K.|editor2-last=Gautam|editor3-first=Ajay K.|editor3-last=Gharami|title=Indigenous Health Care and Ethno-medicine|publisher=Sarup & Sons|year=2006|isbn=9788176257244|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=69vXiaSP09gC&pg=PA76 76]}}</ref> Dickinson Tevi of the Mama Graon Project has expressed concerns that due to Western influence, the use of traditional names is dying out; he described traditional names as a vital link between children and their cultures and customs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.vu/content/mama-graon-director-warns-customs-dying|title=Mama Graon Director warns customs dying|work=Vanuatu Daily Post|date=2011-09-15|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref>
Traditional names may be given at birth,<ref name="OHCHR"/> or bestowed in adulthood by chiefs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.vu/content/kilman-gets-invite-malekula%E2%80%99s-council-chiefs|title=Kilman gets invite from Malekula’s Council of Chiefs|work=Vanuatu Daily Post|date=2011-01-27|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref> Chiefs may also remove a traditional name so bestowed; in 2012, the chiefs of [[Tanna (island)|Tanna]] and then-[[President of Vanuatu]] [[Iolu Abil]] came to an agreement that Abil would no longer use the traditional name "Kaniapnin".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.vu/content/president%E2%80%99s-traditional-name-removed|first=Godwin|last=Ligo|title=President's traditional name removed|work=Vanuatu Daily Post|date=2012-05-10|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref> Land tribunals may look at custom names as one factor in attempting to determine who has the right of usage of disputed [[custom land]], as custom names are also sometimes tied to [[toponymy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypost.vu/content/how-ambaean-named-tasso|first=Len|last=Garae|title=How Ambaean is named Tasso|work=Vanuatu Daily Post|date=2012-02-14|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref> For example, in central and southern Vanuatu, men's custom names make reference to the place where their clan's founding ancestors first appeared, known in [[Bislama]] as ''stamba''.<ref>{{cite book|first=Trevor H. B.|last=Sofield|chapter=Empowerment and Sustainability through Village Ownership: The Ghol, Vanuatu|title=Empowerment for Sustainable Tourism Development|publisher=Emerald Group Publishing|year=2003|isbn=9780080439464|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=fONGI8AjVpQC&pg=PA259 259]}}</ref>
