'''Rabi'ah ibn al-Harith''' ({{lang-ar|ربيعة بن الحارث}})<ref>Other transliterations include "Rabah ibn al-Harith"</ref> (c.566-c.640) was a first cousin and [[sahaba|companion]] of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]].

==Family==
He was a son of [[Al-Harith ibn Abd al-Muttalib]] of the [[Banu Hashim|Hashim]] clan of the [[Quraysh]] in [[Mecca]].<ref name=Tabari39>Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari. ''Tarikh al-Rusul wa'l-Muluk''. Translated by Landau-Tasseron, E. (1998). ''Volume 39: Biographies of the Prophet's Companions and Their Successors''. Albany: State University of New York Press.</ref>{{rp|62,98}}

He married his cousin Umm al-Hakam bint al-Zubayr and they had nine children.<ref name=Saad8>Muhammad ibn Saad. ''Kitab al-Tabaqat al-Kabir''. Translated by Bewley, A. (1995). ''The Women of Madina''. London: Ta-Ha Publishers.</ref>{{rp|34}}<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|198}}
#Muhammad.
#Abdullah.
#Abbas. He had a son named Rahman buried in Jhang
#al-Harith.
#Abdshams.
#Abdulmuttalib, who narrated hadith from Muhammad and settled in Syria.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|63,97}}
#Umayya.
#Another son, variously named Adam, Tammam or Iyas, the victim of the bloodwit case.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|62-63}}
#Arwa "the Elder", from whom Rabi'ah took his ''kunya'' '''Abu Arwa'''.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|288}}

==Conversion to Islam==
It is said that Rabi'ah did not fight at the [[Battle of Badr]] in 624 because he was in Syria at the time.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|62}}

In 627, at the time of the [[Battle of the Ditch]], he converted to [[Islam]] and emigrated to [[Medina]].<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|62}}

==Bloodwit case==
Rabi'ah's son Adam was a small child living with a foster-mother from the [[Banu Bakr|Bakr]] tribe. The Bakr were at war with the [[Banu Hudhayl|Hudhayl]]. Adam crept out in front of the tents and was caught in the cross-fire of the battle. A rock thrown by a Hudhayl man hit and crushed his head, which killed him.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|61,98}}

Rabi'ah intended to demand blood-money or a counter-killing from the Hudhayl for the death of his son. Before this could happen, Muhammad [[Conquest of Mecca|conquered]] Mecca. On that day Muhammad cancelled all bloodwit debts and he specifically named Rabi'ah's case as the first to be cancelled.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|61,98}} However, Ibn Ishaq asserts that the cancellation was declared two years later, at the [[Farewell Pilgrimage]] of 632.<ref name=Ishaq/>{{rp|650-651}}

<blockquote>All blood shed in the pagan period is to be left unavenged. The first claim on blood I abolish is that of Ibn Rabia ibn Al-Harith ibn Abdalmuttalib. It is the first blood shed in the pagan period which I deal with.<ref name=Ishaq/>{{rp|651}}<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|61,98}}</blockquote>

Hence Muhammad prevented Rabi'ah from claiming revenge from the killer.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|61,98}}

==Later life==
Rabī'ah and his brother [[Abu Sufyan ibn al-Harith|Abū Sufyān]] were among the ten people who did not flee in the [[Battle of Hunayn]].<ref name=Ishaq>Muhammad ibn Ishaq. ''Sirat Rasul Allah''. Translated by Guillaume, A. (1955). ''The Life of Muhammad''. Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref>{{rp|569}}<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|62}}

He is involved in the [[Hadith of the ten promised paradise]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

Rabi'ah died after 636 but before 644.<ref name=Tabari39/>{{rp|19,21,62,98}}

